Data Exploration

Top 10 Reported Species

What is the most commonly reported species from the Felidae Family in the CITES database?

#data viz of most commonly reported species

#Count instances per Taxon
species_count <- cites %>%
  count(taxon)  

#Merge counts and common names
top_species <- species_count %>%
  left_join(common_names, by = "taxon")  

#Arrange and select top 10 species
top_species <- top_species %>%
  arrange(n) %>%                          
  slice_max(n, n = 10)                   

#Plot top 10 species
ggplot(top_species, aes(x = reorder(common_name, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(label = comma(n)), hjust = 1.2, color = "white") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = "Individuals Reported", 
       x = NULL,
       title = expression("Top 10 CITES Reported Species in " * italic("Felidae") * " Family from 1975-2024")) +
   scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0,0)), labels = comma)

Purpose / Source

What is the most common purpose (captive breeding, hunting, circus, etc.) for top 10 cat transactions?

The reported purpose of the transaction is shown as a one-letter code:

  • B Breeding in captivity or artificial propagation

  • E Educational

  • G Botanical garden

  • H Hunting trophy

  • L Law enforcement/judicial/forensic

  • M Medical (including biomedical research)

  • N Reintroduction or introduction into the wild

  • P Personal

  • Q Circus or travelling exhibition

  • S Scientific

  • T Commercial

  • Z Zoo

top_cats %>%
  filter(year >= 2022 & year <= 2024) %>% 
  group_by(purpose) %>%

Source codes:

  • C Animals bred in captivity in accordance with Resolution Conf. 10.16 (Rev.), as well as parts and derivatives thereof, exported under the provisions of Article VII, paragraph 5

  • D Appendix-I animals bred in captivity for commercial purposes in operations included in the Secretariatâs Register, in accordance with Resolution Conf. 12.10 (Rev.Â CoP15), and Appendix-I plants artificially propagated for commercial purposes, as well as parts and derivatives thereof, exported under the provisions of Article VII, paragraph 4, of the Convention

  • F Animals born in captivity (F1 or subsequent generations) that do not fulfil the definition of âbred in captivityâ in Resolution Conf. 10.16 (Rev.), as well as parts and derivatives thereof

  • I Confiscated or seized specimens (may be used with another code)

  • O Pre-Convention specimens R Ranched specimens: specimens of animals reared in a controlled environment, taken as eggs or juveniles from the wild, where they would otherwise have had a very low probability of surviving to adulthood

  • U Source unknown (must be justified)

  • W Specimens taken from the wild

Across Time

How has the number of wildlife traded within the Felidae family changed over the years?

felidae_trade_trend <- top_cats %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(total_trade = n(), .groups = "drop")  # Count occurrences per year
ggplot(felidae_trade_trend, aes(x = year, y = total_trade)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue", size = 1) +  
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 2) +  
  labs(title = "Wildlife Trade Trends in the Felidae Family (1975-2024)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Total Transactions") +
  theme_minimal()

2013: CITES CoP16 added new trade restrictions on big cats, pangolins, and tropical birds.

2016: CITES CoP17 introduced stronger protections for species like African lions (Panthera leo), with new regulations limiting the export of wild lion parts (e.g., bones used in traditional medicine).

2019: CITES CoP18 imposed stricter trade regulations on cheetahs (Acinonyx jubatus), frequently trafficked as exotic pets.

felidae_trade_purpose <- top_cats %>%
  filter(year >= 2000) %>%  
  group_by(year, purpose) %>%
  summarize(total_trade = n(), .groups = "drop")

ggplot(felidae_trade_purpose, aes(x = year, y = total_trade, fill = purpose)) +
  geom_area(alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(title = "Purpose of Felidae Trade Over Time (2000 - Present)",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Total Transactions") +
  theme_minimal()
